<br>
I usually keep both of them memorized, because sometimes it's nice to have that extra little bit of invulnerability.<br>
<br>
Here are some things I use DA and DB for:<br>
<br>
1. Low on health and about to die.. it's nice to have those few seconds of invulnerability to try and run away or let a warrior get aggro from you. Unfortunately, if you're too low on health the monster will usually turn back on you when DA wears off.. but such is life.<br>
<br>
2. Jumping fun. Cast DA and jump off something high ... like jumping into the pass to Kael, or off the top of the cliff leading into High Keep.  Always a fun time, if you like butterflies in your tummy.<br>
<br>
3. Emergency spell resistance - say you're swimming to Siren's Grotto and invisibility fails on you just before you hit the cave entrance. You can cast this and just swim past the sirens and ignore their spells. Saves someone having to re-invis you.<br>
<br>
4. Speaking of swimming... ever been stuck underwater, and breath about to run out? Cast Divine Aura and you have another 18 seconds of breath.. which should hopefully be enough to get yourself out of the water or at least a breath of air.<br>
<br>
5. And more swimming.. a trip through lava can be made painless with Divine Aura.<br>
<br>
6. Aggro control after a complete heal. Don't wait until you get low on health to cast. If you gain aggro after a complete heal, get it back to your tank as soon as possible. This is probably the easiest way.<br>
<br>
7. Ever run through the Great Divide and get attacked by a giant, only to realize that you don't have any offensive spells loaded? Cast Divine Aura, sit and memorize your spells, then stand up and nuke that giant. Avoids having to train or run away.<br>
<br>
8. Corpse draggings from REALLY nasty places. I used Divine Aura to pull a body out from under Nagafen this past weekend.  Cast DA, run in, grab the body, drag it back, then run out of range of Naggy and /camp to clear aggro.  It's nerve-wracking but it does work. I've also done similar corpse drags in Unrest when I was much younger, since invisibility wasn't good enough to sneak past the undead, nor was invisibility to undead good enough to sneak past the werewolves and mushroom men.<br>
<br>
9. Checking &quot;hot&quot; zone entrances for aggro. Zoning into a place like Umbral Plains can be instant death if there are monsters at the entrance. Cast Divine Aura, then zone; if there are monsters on the other side, you should have enough time remaining to retreat back without worrying about getting stunned. Or, use it to run through a &quot;hot&quot; zone pass, like going into Akheva Ruins from Maiden's Eye.<br>
<br>
10. Fooling spellcasters during a duel.  If fighting a wizard, you can cast Divine Aura while they try to nail you with Ice Comet or lures or whatever. They may think you're resisting their spells. It could be tough to trick them again though.<br>
<br>
Any others? let's hear some =)<br>
